node.text:
Just like consumer cars have to undergo crash testing, so do commercial semitrucks. While some of these tests are the same that production cars undergo, others are designed specifically for trucks. 

Thanks to trucking companies like Volvo and Scania as well as the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, safety standards for these trucks are only improving.

node.text: Vietnamese woodworker Truong Van Dao built a fully drivable wooden Bugatti. It’s one third the size of an actual car, but a near replica of the luxury automaker’s $8.9 million Centodieci hypercar. We explore how he did the entire project in just 40 days.

node.title: How to build a fully drivable wooden Bugatti

node.text: A wave of upcoming hypercars claim to accelerate 0 to 60 mph in as little as 1.7 seconds. However, nothing has been verified. The reality is that no production car has ever managed an official 0 to 60 time of under 2 seconds. There's a reason for that. We break down how current technology has created that limit, and what could be done to break it.

node.title: Why going 0 to 60 mph in under 2 seconds is almost impossible

node.text:
In 2019, the Bugatti Chiron Super Sport 300  became the first production car to drive 300 mph. This was almost 15 years after the Bugatti Veyron became the first to reach 250. So why did it take so long for automakers to build a car just 50 mph faster? We explore what makes 300 mph such a difficult benchmark to reach and what automakers like Bugatti have been doing to chase it.

#cars #speed #bugatti #sportscar

node.title: Why It's Almost Impossible For Cars To Go 300 Miles Per Hour

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of a team of three women working with the headline, "Why diverse tech teams make better products."

node.text:
According to a recent survey of 1,000 industry workers, a vast majority of tech employees believe technology products are not diverse enough, and neither are the teams that design them. 

Data suggests that ethnic and gender diversity make companies more likely to succeed, but leadership often fails to acknowledge the problem.

Read more about this story by clicking the link in our bio.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of a team of three women working with the headline, "Why diverse tech teams make better products."

Text graphic with the text, "Only 16% of women and racial-minority employees said they were well-represented on tech teams. 84% of all tech employees said their products were not inclusive, according to a survey of 1,000 tech employees by the consulting firm Capgemini."

Text graphic with the text, "A 2018 McKinsey report found companies in the top 25% for gender diversity on executive teams outperformed more homogenous companies by 21%. Ethnic diversity also made companies 33% more likely to have industry-leading profitability. For Silicon Valley, the solution proposed by tech diversity leaders is to incorporate more viewpoints into the product. That begins by diversifying the field of product management."

Text graphic with the quote, "There are generations in the workplace with different sets of values, where this lack of inclusion is less acceptable. You either adapt to that, or you'll lose out on talent and top-end consumers," attributed to Zari Zahra, founder and chief product officer of Spekit.
Photo of the Olympic flag with the headline, "TikTok and Twitter removed videos exposing gay athletes on dating apps in Tokyo's Olympic Village."

node.text:
TikTok and Twitter removed several videos from their platforms that exposed gay Olympians in Tokyo using the dating app Grindr. The videos risked outing some athletes as gay and posed a potential threat to Olympians from countries where homosexuality is still outlawed.

In the videos, creators scrolled through various Olympians’ profiles, where some users showed their full faces and gave identifying details. Some of the athletes identified themselves as being from countries known for anti-LGBTQ politics.

Read the full story by clicking the link in our bio.

(Credit: Getty Images)

node.text:
Mark Zuckerberg said this week that Facebook will transform into a metaverse company. Metaverse is the next iteration of the internet and will expand on the physical and digital worlds. It's Zuckerberg's own futuristic mission after his peers catapulted to the edge of space.

Click the link in our bio to learn more about this story.

(Credit: Getty Images)
#MarkZuckerberg #Facebook #Metaverse #VirtualUniverse #SocialMedia

node.accessibility_caption: Photo showing Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg on stage at an Oculus developers conference in 2016 with the headline, "Mark Zuckerberg is no astronaut, so he's rocketing Facebook into a virtual universe instead."

Text explainer with the headline, "Billionares in space" and the description, "Richard Branson rocketed to the edge of space. So did Jeff Bezos just days later. Elon Musk has grand plans for interplanetary life, too. But Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg is one tech billionaire that's not following suit. Instead, he unveiled his own futuristic ambitions recently: positioning his company as the center of the so-called metaverse."

Text explainer with the headline "What is the metaverse?" and the description, "think of the metaverse as what will come after the internet. It's a virtual universe that will straddle the physical and digital worlds, allowing people to live and interact in real-time in both of them."

Text explainer with the headline, "A metaverse company" and the description, "Zuckerberg said Facebook would evolve from a social media company into a "metaverse company." And Facebook's Andrew Bosworth said Monday that the company is even building out a designated executive team to oversee progress towards the metaverse vision. It'll exist within Facebook's virtual reality branch."

Text explainer with the headline, "Virtual reality today" and the description, "Virtual reality can currently make you feel like you’re in another room, meet with someone thousands of miles away, or allow for new experiences that would otherwise be impossible in the real world. Andrew Bosworth now wants to remove the current physical limitations that disrupt transitions between virtual worlds within the next five years."

Photo by Tech Insider on July 27, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, phone, screen and text that says 'Premium INSIDER Your Apple laptop is probably repaired at a facility workers say is a 'sweatshop' CSAT Salutions'.

node.text:
If you're ever unlucky enough to spill a latte between the keys of your $1,300 MacBook Pro or shatter its screen, your first stop would probably be Apple's website, where you could schedule an appointment to take it to a nearby Apple Store.

Surrounded by pristine white walls, floor-to-ceiling windows, and blond wood tables, you would wait for help at Apple's Genius Bar. A friendly, casually dressed employee would say hello and listen to your problem. Then you'd surrender your expensive aluminum brick and watch it disappear behind closed doors for repair.

But behind that gleaming white facade, your laptop would likely begin a journey to a very different place. 

Read the full story at the link in our bio.

(Credit: Apple; CSAT Solutions; Samantha Lee/Insider)

node.text:
A Tesla owner posted a clip to Twitter on Thursday showing his vehicle attempt to slow down after mistaking an unusually low and yellow moon as a yellow traffic light. Other Tesla drivers have posted similar videos of their car’s self-driving feature glitching.

The “Traffic Light and Stop Sign Control” feature, released via a software update in early 2020, is still in beta, and owners have to switch it on manually.

Tesla CEO Elon Musk hopes to eventually make the self-driving system even safer than a human driver.

Click the link in our bio to see the full story.

(Credit: Reuters)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of a person driving a Tesla car with the headline, "Tesla's Full Self-Driving tech keeps getting fooled by the moon, billboards, and Burger King signs."

Text graphic with the text, "A Tesla owner posted a clip to Twitter on Thursday showing his vehicle attempt to slow down after mistaking an unusually low and yellow moon as a yellow traffic light. In the past, Tesla owners have also reported their vehicles mistaking the sun for a red light, a stop sign on a billboard for the real thing, and a roadside Burger King sign as a stop sign."

Text graphic with the text, "Tesla doesn't claim that Full Self-Driving can perfectly react to traffic lights and stop signs just yet. The "Traffic Light and Stop Sign Control" feature was released via a software update in early 2020 and is still in beta. Owners have to switch it on manually. The billionaire Jeff Bezos went to the edge of space on Tuesday in Blue Origin's New Shepard rocket. The suborbital rocket has a domed, wide capsule on top for passengers — giving it a phallic profile. New Shepard's characteristic design makes it more stable and optimizes cabin space, experts said.

A photo of Jeff Bezos laughing as he speaks about his flight on Blue Origin's New Shepard on Tuesday with the text, "The New Shepard rocket's tumescent shape was low-hanging fruit to social-media users who were quick to point out the craft's phallic design and wonder whether that design meant its billionaire passenger was compensating for something."

Text slide with the headline "Purposeful Design" saying, "New Shepard's characteristic shape was designed to optimize cabin space for up to six passengers and maximize the rocket's stability when coming back to Earth, according to Pedros Llanos, an engineer and professor of spaceflight operations at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University."

Text slide saying, "The main reason the design looks like this is because Jeff's first goal is to send people to space, so everything revolves around having four to six people in the cabin and so maximizing cabin volume,"  from Pedros Llamos,  an engineer and professor of spaceflight operations at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University.

Text explainer with the headline "Skinnier Design" saying, "Like most rockets, New Shepard has a propellant-filled booster that helps blast its capsule toward space. The higher in space a rocket's objective is, the more propellant it needs to hold in order to power its journey. So a booster carrying a spacecraft bound for the orbiting International Space Station, like SpaceX's Falcon 9 rocket, is going to be taller and larger than a booster for a rocket like New Shepard that's designed to go only to the very edge of space."

Text graphic with the text, "History: Asphyxiation challenges, sometimes called the "choking game," predate TikTok and even social media. While they previously spread by word-of-mouth, Time Magazine reported in 2018 that online platforms made information about them more accessible, which may have led more children to try it alone rather than with friends. A 2008 CDC study identified 82 "probable choking-game deaths" between youths ages 6-19 from 1995-2007."

Text graphic with the text, "TikTok: It's unclear whether the Oklahoma child had a TikTok account or actively used the platform. A spokesperson for the Bethany Police Department told Insider that the department could not provide information on the child, but said that investigators were looking into information from family and friends regarding his TikTok presence. TikTok's search guardrails do make it difficult to find content related to the challenge and Insider could not find evidence that the challenge has recently been trending on the app."
